Title: Staged Refresh Timers for RSVP  
Author: Ping Pan, Henning Schulzrinne 
Note: KeywordsRSVP, soft state.  
Abstract: In the current RSVP design [2], there is no reliability mechanism for control message delivery. Instead RSVP relies on periodic refresh between routers to maintain reservation states. This approach has several potential problems in a congested network. End systems send PATH and RESV messages to set up RSVP connections. If the first PATH or RESV message is accidentally lost, an upstream router will have to wait for the entire duration of a refresh cycle to retransmit another copy of the lost message. If a tear-down message (a PATHTEAR or a RESVTEAR) is dropped at a congested link, a reservation will not be removed until the RSVP cleanup timer expires. The above problems may not be acceptable for certain applications. In this paper, we present a RSVP extension to support fast and reliable message delivery. The extension is backward compatible and is easy to be adapted to the current implementation. In the paper, we will address several design issues extensively. 
